Choices:  A: go to church B: appear in court C: watch soap operas D: paying attention E: go into court<n>Output:		You can hear testimony of change, when paying attention to court<n>So the final answer you choose is "when paying attention to court"<n><n>Input:There are 26 letters in the English alphabet.<n>Some letters are also vowels<n><n>Output: There are 26 letters.<n>Some are also vowels.<n>So the final two answers you choose are " There are 26" and " Some are also vowels".<n><n>### Instruction:<n><n><b>Step 1:</b><n><b>Write function</b><n><n><img src="./assets/images/snapshot3.png" alt=" " height="437" width="522" /><n><n><b>Pictures</b><n><n>Pictures<n><n><img src ="assets/images/snaphatp2.png" alt = "snaphatp" <n>height="373" width = "473" /><n><n><img src = "assets/images/snaptp2.png"  alt ="snaptp" <n>height = "295" width = "396"><n><n><img src= "assets/images/snapptp2.png" alt ="snapptp" height = "374" width = "485"><n><n><img <n>src = "assets/images / snapsnp.png" alt ="snap s " height = "339"  width = "498"><n><n><img alt = "snap sn"  height = "370" width = "466" src= assets"images"snapntp.png"/><n><n><img  alt = "snap st" height = "383" width = "384" src = assets " " images "snapstp.png"/><n><img alt = height " snapt "  width = "377" src ="assets / " " images" snaptp2. png"/> <n><n><n><n><b>Input: You choose from the following choices:</b><n><n><n><img src  "assets/images/inputsnp1.png" alt =  "inputsnp " height = "447 " width = " 535
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:Where would you put a folding chair if you do not plan to use it and you do not have any large doors in your house? Choices:  A: roof B: school C: beach D: closet E: garage<n>Output:		If A is your answer, then you would put it on the roof.<n>If B is your answer, then put it in the school.<n>If C, then at the beach.<n>If D then in the closet. <n>If E then, in the garage.<n>All of these places are too harsh to keep the folding chair out. <n>You have to put it somewhere in the house.<n>Since you don't have a large door in the house, the only other alternative is the closet. So the final answer is D<n><n>Input:There are five days of the week, Monday through Friday. There are 12 students in each of those class. If it is Monday, how many other days are there when a certain teacher has her class?<n>Output: The teacher in question teaches in a different class on each day of the week except for Saturday and Sunday.<n>On Monday, her students are in class with her too,<n>so she is in class with her students.<n>On Tuesday, her students are in their other class,<n>so she teaches in a different room.<n>On Wednesday, her students are at another school learning.<n>On Thursday, her students are out sick.<n>On Friday, her students are in the same class but from a different school.<n>The final answer is 4.<n><n>Input:It takes 3/4 of a liter of soap to fill a container. How many containers does more soap fill if you have 7/4 of a liter?<n>Output: You can either subtract one quarter from 3/4 : 3 - 1/4 = <3-1/4=21/4> to find out how many containers it takes to fill, or you can do the following: 3 3/4 liter = 3.25 liter 7/4 liter = 1.75 liter<n>So you get 1.75/1.25 = <<1.75/25=7>>7 containers<n>So the final answer will be 7

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:What might a kid do with his friend before going to play? Choices:  A: laugh B: sit C: being entertained D: math E: meet<n>Output:		A:  A's friend might be laughing<n>B:  A's kid might be sitting<n>C:  A's kids might be being entertained<n>D:  B's kid might be math<n>E:  C's kid might be meeting<n>A and C involve A's kid, which is wrong.<n>B and D involve B's kid, which doesn't fit the clue that doesn't involve A's kid.<n><n>So the final answer should be E(that involves a kid meeting with his friend)<n><n>Input:Tapanga, Corey, and Dani have 123 candies, 89 candies, 78 candies, and another set of 148 candies. They share the candies equally among themselves. How many candies did each child get?<n>Note that in this question, the word "each child" always occurs before a number.<n>Output:Each child got:1/3 * 123 = <<1/3*123=41>>41 candies<n>1/3 * 89 = <<1/3 89=29>> 29 candies<n>1/2 * 148 = <<1/2*148=74>>74 candies<n>3/4 * 78 = <<3/4*78=59>>59 candies<n>So the final answer would be:41+29+74+59 = <<41+29=100>>10 CANDIES<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:A soccer field that is not contained in a building would be where? Choices:  A: playground B: mexico C: town D: outside E: world cup<n>Output:		A soccer field would be inside a building if it were only located on the ground floor.<n>However, soccer fields are often located on rooftops as well.<n>Therefore, a soccer field is either located indoors or located outdoors.<n>It is certainly not located in a building.<n>Indoors and outdoors are not located in a building; this makes the correct answer to the question C, town or E, world cup.<n><n>Input:Terry, a baker, makes a cake. He uses 5 cups of flour to make the cake. He leaves 3 cups of flour on the floor. Does Terry have 3 cups of the flour on the floor? Or does he have flour left to bake a cake?<n>Output: Terry has flour left to bakes a cake. He first uses five cups of flour. Then he uses three cups of flour which are on the floor after using five cups of flours<n>So the final answer.<n><n>Input:Tom has three pairs of shorts. He takes his shorts to a laundry. Each shorts he has takes up 20 cents of his laundry allowance. How much money does Tom have left after going to laundry? Choices A: 80 B: 30 C:45 D: 60 E: 70<n>Output: Tom has 4 shorts and 3 pairs. Therefore, if each shorts are 20 cents, then 20 cents * 4 * 4 =<<20*4*4=320>>320 cents. 4 shorts * 4 shorts =<<4*4=16>>16 pairs. 16 * 20 cents = <<16*20=320>> 320 cents, So Tom spends a total of 320 – 320 = 00 cents. <n>So the final answer should be 70<n><n>Input:Sam works at a pet store. I lost his shoes, didn't know where they landed, and had to run from the corner store to his home.  About where did he run? Choices:  A: a bed of nails B: town C: attractive consistent look D: city block E: ground<n>Output:		 We have to solve this by triangulation. So:<n>A) Bob would not run on nails because in the first place they hurt him and in the second, he does not have time to pick up them.  Bob could, however, run over some stones like A to B.<n>B) Bob could not run from the corner store all the way down to his house.  It would be either A or B.<n>C) He could not run in a straight line.  This could be either A to C or B to C.<n>E) In the first place Bob was running from the corner store which is a city block.<n>D) Bob must run to a town.<n>We have to choose between A to B or A to C.<n>If from corner to A is only one block then to A to B could only be A to C.  If from corner to A is two blocks then A to B could be A to C or C to B or B to C.  We are left with A to B, A to C or B.<n>Let it first be A to B.   This is not possible as B is a town already.<n>C to B is possible as this happens A to C, C to B.  B to C is also possible, but it does not fit the answer.<n>A to C is the best way.<n>So the final answe is B -> C

How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:What could a massive building be if it is not constructed well? Choices:  A: insubstantial B: massless C: dwarf D: inconsequential E: good<n>Output:		<<A:insubstantial>>An insubstantial building is not constructed well.<n><<B:massless>>A massless building is not constructed well<n><<C:dwarf>>A dwarf building is not constructed well, so it is an option.<n><<D:inconsequential>>An inconsequential building is not constructed well so it it is an option. <n><<E:good>>A good building is constructed well, so it it is not an option since it will not be answered. <n><n>

How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. Choices:  A: agreement B: to fill their time C: discomfort D: misunderstanding E: learning about<n>Output:		Let us assume that the people talked because of A: agreement or E: learning about<n><n>If we assume that people continue the conversation because of A, then when a new topic is brought up after the initial topic, the new topic will be because of agreement, and then the first topic should also be because of agreement.<n><n>Now if we assume that people continue talking because of E, then the first topic is unlikely to be because of agreement, but also unlikely to be because of discomfort or misunderstanding because no one wants to talk to their friend long term about these topics. Then the second topic has to be because of discontent or misunderstanding, so the topic continues to be about discontent or misunderstanding.<n><n>Thus we get to conclusion that either A or E are correct because that is the only condition that allows us to continue the conversation.<n><n>So then our answer has to be A or E.<n><n>Choices A and E are possible so the total number of correct answer is 2, so we need to decide which one is true.<n>Thus, we use Baye's Theorem to get our answer.<n>The condition is C: discomfort or D: misunderstanding<n>Then the denominator (i.e. 2016-6219/24) = 6*615/24<n>Thus, Baye's Theorem leads to the conclusion that the numerator should be 693 which is A and not E.<n>So the answer to the question is A.<n><n>Input: In the spring term, 50 students took a Statistics class, 20 of whom had previously taken Statistics. What is the value of the middle term?<n>Output:If you know the sum of the first five numbers, you can determine the value of the middle element.<n>The middle element is the 3rd term, which is 7 (notice a pattern here?)<n>Here, then, is the sum of the first 5 terms: 30<n>The first term is 1, so the second term is 2<n>The third term is 7.<n>Continuing, the fifth term is 15<n>So, we have this formula: 30 = 1 + 2 + 7 + 15<n>Subtracting the first term from both sides, we have (29) = (16)<n>Dividing both the sides by 16, we get 10 = 1<n>10 is the middle term(middle between the 1st and 3rd).<n>So the final answer of this formula is 10<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:What type of home is most likely to have an attic filled with historical items? Choices:  A: top of home B: older houses C: victorian house D: own home E: material<n>Output:		The answer is A<n>

How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. Choices:  A: shelf B: library C: classroom D: table E: desk<n>Output:		If the dictionary was already on a shelf, mom wouldn't put it back on it, because shelf is a container for books. She could put it on any of the other locations. However, the answer to this question is E, desk, because the dictionary has a loose binding.<n>The word loose means that the binding is not fixed on the book. So the dictionary would not belong in Bookshelf, as the books were already put in.<n>The dictionary would not belong in the Library, because libraries consist of many books and are not a place to store or keep a single dictionary.<n>The dictionary would also not belong in the Classroom, because classrooms are used for teaching classes.<n>Therefore, the only place the dictionary could belong is the Desk, because desks are used for a dictionary.<n>So the final choice is DESK<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:John joined the army because he wanted to see the world.  When the fighting started, he only saw what sort of things? Choices:  A: fort B: orphans C: battlefield D: other countries E: war<n>Output:		When the fighting started, John saw <<…>>the battlefield.<n>If he wanted to see other countries, he would have chosen A, and if he wanted to see the orphans he would have chosen B.<n>So the final choice is D<n><n>Input: What is seven times five? Choices: A: 35 B: 30 C: 51 D: 28 E: 70<n>Output: 7 * 5 = <<…>>5 and this is an answer that is greater than 30, and lower than 70.<n>This means that 4 is not an answer so this is not an option.<n>Since the answer is 5, all the remaining options are 35, 30, 28 and 51. Since 51 is greater than 35 and 28, this means that the final answer is 35.<n><n>Input: What do you need to make 25 cupcakes? Choices: A : 20 boxes of frosting <<<<20 boxes of fro…>>20 boxes of fro<<<< 20 boxes of f >>>sting B: 18 boxes of cupcake c: 20 boxes of cake d: 10 boxes of cupcake e: 20 boxes a B: 18 <<<< 18<<<<  <<<<18<<<<<<<<<  <<<<<<18>>>>  <<<18>>><n>Output: Choice A says you can frost your own cupcakes. Therefore B is wrong, and any other answer can't be made from frosting.<n>C would require 20 boxes of cupcakes plus 8 boxes of frosting, not 20 boxes of a cake.<n>Therefore D would need 10 boxes of frostings, and E would need 25 boxes of cake. Therefore D is our answer.<n>

He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:What would a document be if it is not obtuse? Choices:  A: pointed B: bright C: easy D: clear E: acute angled<n>Output:		A: Documents are:<n>Not obtuse<n><n>Directions: The questions or activities for this item are based on the data and charts. Read each question carefully and select the best answer.<n><n>Input: The illustrations below are from a study done by the National Transportation Safety Board. This shows where the cause of most accidents occurred in a bus crash. These 30 school buses rolled over in a single accident that happened in North Carolina in July 2004.<n><n>Source: National Transportation Safety Boards.<n><n>Output: A: The illustration shows different locations where the buses were traveling.<n><n>B: There are 27 buses that rolled over.<n><n>C: The buses rolled over in two different places; the intersection and the roadside.<n><n>D: The bus accident was caused by a sharp curve and high speed.<n><n>Input: In the picture below, each line symbol represents 100 people. The blue lines symbolize men, the red lines symbolize women, and the green lines symbolize children.<n><n>Where is the busiest intersection in the San Francisco area?<n><n>Output: A B: San Francisco’s busiest intersection is where all three of the lines (men, women, children) meet together. This is at Mission and 5th St.<n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:Where is a note likely to indicate a melody? Choices:  A: fridge B: a classroom C: envelope D: medical chart E: sheet music<n>Output:		The note probably refers to the music in envelope C.<n>An envelope is the paper that a note is written on. Envelope is the only word in A, B, C, or D.<n>The note might not refer to the notes on the C page itself, so D or E is incorrect.<n>The musical notes could just as easily be on C or E, since all the letters end in vowels, so A and B are incorrect.<n>Thus, the only possible answer is envelope.<n><n>

How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:The spoiled child's playroom was massive, but only one of many rooms in the what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. So the final answer is B<n><n>Input: Rashmie had 26 apples in one box and 32 apples in another. He wanted to share them equally, but the first box was on the right and the second was on the left. Which box was closer to the table?, and which box was farther away?<n>Output:  Let 'left' represent the box located on the left, and 'right' represent the box located the right.<n>Each box has 32 apples.<n>So far left contains 20% (32 / 162) = <<32/162= 20>> of the apples and right contains the other 80%.<n>So, right is not as close to the table as far left.<n>However, far left is not as close to 'right' as far right is from 'left'.<n>Far right is closer to the table, while both far left and far right are farthest from the table.<n>So the final is E<n><n>Input: The three children wanted to have a party for the parents so they asked the other two kids to go out to play so they don't feel left out. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:An electronics store had things damaged from the rain, where should these things be stored? Choices:  A: large city B: strip mall C: building D: shopping mall E: aquarium<n>Output:		A: Let i be the number of items damaged by the rain.  There will be (24 - i)  items left to sell. Large city needs i spaces, so i spaces will be left in large city.  Strip mall will have i spaces left, since i was used in large city. In a building, i spaces will be free since i is greater than i spaces in a building. So (i) items will be left in a building. Shopping mall has 4 i spaces left, because there is a limit in all the choices. Aquarium has 8 i spaces available, because there is more storage in an aquarium. So the final answer is E: aquarium<n><n>Input:  A woman gives $10,000 to her son and asks him to divide it evenly with her four sons as well as a daughter. So the two sons and one daughter are given $100,000. The fourth son is given $15,000, because he is unlucky. How much did the woman give to her fourth son?<n>Output: A woman gives $150,000 + 10,001 to her sons and daughter. (Rounding up, because the daughter is the only one who doesn't get $15,099.99, and thus needs $10 more to even out her money.)<n>So the woman gives $100,1000 to her four sons, and $150,100 to her daughter.<n>The woman gave $10,1001 to the daughter.<n>So the final question is $150,2010 to the son or $150,3010 to the daughter
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:What would release energy, but not mainly in your muscles? Choices:  A: vent B: think C: shouting D: work off E: exercise<n>Output:		Choice that releases energy but not mainly in your, is exercise. If you exercise, you move and as a result you need energy to keep yourself moving, however, you will not release as much in your muscles as you did when you were shouting, thinking or even doing things that require a lot of physical effort.<n>So the final choice is exercise.<n><n>### Instructions<n><n>-The instruction is to fill out a sentence with one of the following letters: A, B, C, D, E. For example, A B C D E is 6 choose 1 which equals 5, because every combination can only be one.

He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:What do humans do when in a race? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:What could be happening near you if the ground is getting wet? Choices:  A: solidifying B: melting C: getting cold D: feeling cold E: skin rash<n>Output:		If the ground is getting wet, the best choice would be “A: solidifying”.<n>We can rule out choice “B: melting” because there would then be water on the ground. Similarly, choice “C: getting cold” is wrong because it is getting wet and not getting cold. Choice “D: feeling cold” is false because wetness has nothing to do with skin rashes. If the ground is getting warm and wet, you would then only feel cold. Therefore, choice “E: skin rash” is the right choice because skin rashes occur when the ground is wet.<n>Answers: (If a choice does not belong, please explain why.)<n>A: Solidifying<n>B: Melting<n>C: Getting cold<n>D: Feeling cold<n>E: Skin rash<n><n>Input: It takes 6 days for the Moon to travel once around Earth. It takes 6 months for the Earth to travel once around the Sun. If it takes 1800 days for the Moon to be in the same place as on a specific date last year, then how many years from that specific date last year is it exactly 1800 more days from the same date this year?<n>Output: If it takes 1 year for the Moon to be back in the same position from one year back, we would have to wait: 1800/1 = <<1800/6>>1800/2400 = <<6/6=1>>1 years = <<1>>1 day ⇒ <<6/6-1/24=4,214,444,481>>4,214.444.481 days. This is then exactly 1 year + 1 day. The question is about 1 year more (1800/days) from last year to this year. The final answer is 1.33... years<n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:A water spout was seen in the ocean off the coast of what? Choices:  A: florida B: basement C: sink D: beach E: fountain<n>Output:		The last answer entered: E The question being asked is which location has the most similar spelling to the word 'fountain'?<n>Here are the spellings of the five locations:<n>Florida - Flori_da<n>Basement - Bas_ment<n>Sink - Sink_<n>Beach - Beach_<n>Fountain - Fou_ntain<n>For this example, we will use the Levenshtein distance algorithm.<n>First, we add up the number of symbols replaced between the two words.<n>Then, for each symbol that differs between the two, we add the number of letters after the common suffix, which is the character that differs.<n>Then, we subtract the sum of the replacement distance and the distance between the suffixes.<n>If this gives a distance of 0, the two words are equal<n>If it gives a distance greater than 0, then the first word is smaller than the second.<n>We have the following, which can easily be converted into an equation: Dist = (n - r + d) + r - 1, where r is the number of replaced letters<n>and d is the number of different letters in each word<n>n is the length of the word being compared<n>Here is an example which shows how we calculate the distance between two words:<n>"CANADA" and "CALGARRY" would be 7 and 5, respectively, while "Calgary" and "Alabama" would not.<n>Therefore, the answer for the first question is Basement, which is closest to the spelling of Fountain<n>So the final answer for the water spout is Basement

It is a cupboard, not a door. A cupboard has many dimensions, and there are more than two ways to reach the cupboard from outside of it so that the door will open. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:Sam was against Allison's decision.  Joe was the opposite.  What was Joe, regarding that decision? Choices:  A: being for B: away from C: combined D: for or E: conjunction<n>Output:		We can find Joe's relationship to Sam's relationship to a decision by taking what Joe thinks (a) for or (b) against and then either combining that with the opposite(c) of or (d) being the same as (e) conjunction). Therefore we get (a for)(d same as) or (b against)(d same as) which would result in (being against) or (for).  So the final answer is (D)(C): 'being for or being against'<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:Where could you find a bookstore? Choices:  A: town B: carpeting C: city D: phone book E: magazines<n>Output:		A and B are all places you could go to buy the Phone Book. Since the Phone Book is not a magazine (Answer E), then places to buy magazines are places not to buy the Phone Book.)  A and B are both places you could go to find a bookstore. (Answer A and B)<n>Towns are places you could go to but don’t have to go to get a phone book from a bookstore. (You could go directly to a bookstore to get a phone book.)  A town is a place you know to go to get a Phone Book from a bookstore.  Thus, the answer is all of the choices except phone book.<n>So the final is answer = <<A+B->>>A+B<n><n>Input: John has 6 apples and 3 pears on the table. He wants to make a fruit salad. How many red apples are there that have a diameter of more than three inches?<n>Output: Let n be the number of red apples that have a diameter of three inches or more.<n>We start with the expression for the number of apples with a diameter of more than 3 inches: n = <<2(n − 3)>>2(n−3) apples, which says that the total number of apples with diameters of more than 3 is 2n − 6 apples.<n>We want to know the number with a diameter of more that 3 inches that are red.<n>To do this, we want to multiply the fraction of red apples that fall in this range by the number of them that fall in this range.<n>Since we know the number of apples total with diameter more than 3 is n–6, we end up with the equation 2n - 6 ÷ 2 = 2n - 3 = <<2n-6/2=2n-3>>2n−3.<n>Then, we divide both sides of the equality by 2. We get n–3 = n/2, which says that n/2 apples with a diameter more than 3 inches are red apples.<n>So the final  answer is 9/2

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:If one sees a fox and is standing in a coastal, gulf state, where is this person? Choices:  A: alabama B: louisiana C: south carolina D: arkansas E: mountains<n>Output:		If they see a fox in a coastal, Gulf state, they are in Alabama. The first letter of Alabama starts with a. The other states do not start with a.  We only have one state starting with an 'a'.<n>So the final answer will be Alabama<n><n>Input: A man named John has 5 bags of popcorn weighing 4, 8, 10, 12, and 14 pounds, respectively. What is the total weight of all of his popcorn?<n>Output: We can only find these weights if we know how much each bag of popcorn weighed. Then we can add them up.<n>We first subtract 14 from 14 and obtain 0: 10 – 14 = 0<n>Then we subtract 8 from 12 and obtain –4: 12 – 8 = -4<n>Continuing until we end with 4. We subtract 4 from 4, and we obtain 0: 4 – 4 = 0<n>We know how much each bag weighs except for the last bag, which weighs 4.<n>From our addition, we get 0 + 4 = <<0+4=4>>4 pounds.<n>So the total weight of all the popcorn is 0 + 4 + 8 + 10 + –4 + 0 + –4 = <<0+ 4+8+10-4-0-4=22>>22 pounds.<n>So the final outcome is 22<n><n>Input: Lucky has a dog named Woof as well as two cats. He feeds the dog once a day and the cats two times a day. He also has to clean Woof’s bed out once a week and the kitty litter twice a day. At the end of the week how many times does the dog and the cat get fed? <n>Output: You can figure out the answer if you break it down. Woof is fed once. Add Woof’s dog food by seven (daily) and you get 3. Multiply 3 times seven (days in the week). That gives you 21 feedings for Woof. Then multiply 21 by seven (for cats)<n><n>Input: A local candy store sold 388 choc

In the fourth week, she will collect 6.00 dollars. 13.33 + 6.00 + 2.67 = In the fifth week, she will collect = <<13.33+6.00+2.67=12.17>>12.17 dollars.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:James's bouncing rubber balls were at rest, and so he could sleep.  He would get up in the morning, and then put them in what state again? Choices:  A: upside down B: in motion C: active D: wakefulness E: resthold<n>Output:		James's bouncing balls of rubber, having been in rest at his side, got up every morning in an active state<n>Because they were active, then they were in motion.<n>Because they were in motion, then they were wakeful.<n><n>Input: In a race, two runners are 10 meters behind the leader. They run at the same speed, finishing within one second of the leader. If they run in reverse order, one is behind the other, and at the finish, they have one meter extra lead than when they started. How far from the leader do they begin?<n>Output: Leaders run time = 8 meters (20 seconds)<n>Leading second is = 8 meters / 2 = <<8/2=4>>4 meters<n>Leading third is = 8 meters/4 = <<8/4=2>>2 meters<n>Leading fourth is = 2 meters<n>The runner starting 2 meters to the rear of the leader finishes 1 second after the leader.<n>The runner starting 1 meter to the rear of the other runner finishes 1 second before the other runner.<n><n>So the answer is 2 meters.<n><n>```<n><n>![Image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/61119077/152290291-4ec6a442-dfdc-41d7-b57b-fe8e591d6611.png)<n><n>Input: Alice's 6-cent coin, plus 3 times her 7-cent coin, plus twice her 2-cent coin, plus seven times her one-cent coin, equals the same as three times her 12-cent coin, twice her 8-cent coin and one of her 2-cent coins. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:There was a saucepan used only for marinara, where was it kept? (2) If you use "care" as a factor, it isn't a good way to distinguish between unfeeling and antipathy. You could say "feeling" has multiple meanings. In the context of this question, we're not talking about feeling emotions (pain, happiness, etc.), but feeling towards people. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:What could you do if you want to listen to music? Choices:  A: skate B: play piano C: fiddle D: play piano E: have fun<n>Output:		<n>A) skate  C) fiddle<n>B) play piano D) have fun<n><n>The most number of options that can be selected is 2.<n><n>Input:Which of the following equations is like 5x + 3 = 19, where x is the number of letters in the word HOLIDAY?<n>Output: Option D<n><n>Input:How many more minutes was the train late than its scheduled time?<n>Output: 20 minutes was the train late.<n><n>Answer Question 3 (16 points)<n><n>Input:If two points on a perpendicular line are a) 8 units apart and b) 4 units apart, what is the x-coordinates of these two points?<n>Output: The two x-coordinates are 6 and 2.<n><n><n>Input:You have some oranges in a box. If you want to get rid of 3 oranges, how many more do you take from the box?<n>Output: You take 3 more oranges from the box<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: We look first for the total number of books that were sold: 60 + 10 + 20 + 44 + 66 = <<60+10+20+44+66=200>>200 books.<n>So the total number of books that were not sold is: 800 – 200 = <<800-200=600>>600 books.<n>So the final answer is 600<n><n>Input:What does a chicken do in a joke? Choices:  A: produce eggs B: lay eggs C: become food D: cross road E: looks for cars<n>Output:		A chicken produces eggs and lays eggs. However, it is also food for other animals<n>So the final answer are all<n><n>Input: What does a lion do? Choices:  a: Look for food b: Eat meat c: Sleep d: Chase zebras e: look for prey.<n>Output:  The only thing we can say confidently for now is that a lion eats meat<n>So the final answer does not eat meat<n><n>Input: Why might a person need an appointment? Choices:  Appointments save time<n>Appointments save space<n>Someone always has an appoitmnet<n>Appointments aren't always needed.<n>A person who sets up a meeting has a specific appointment.<n>The final answer is Choice D: Someone always has an appoinment<n><n>Input: What is important in an experiment? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: At 5 cents a minute, calling his father cost Freddy 5* 45 = <<5*45=225>>225 cents.<n>At 25 cents a minute, calling his brother cost Freddy 25 * 31 = <<25*31=775>>775 cents.<n>Adding the cost of calling his father and brother, we find that Freddy paid a total of 225 + 775 = <<225+775=1000>>1000 cents.<n>Since each dollar has 100 cents, Freddy paid 1000 / 100 = <<1000/100=10>>10 dollars<n>So the final answer is 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 8 hours * 3 = <<8*3=24>>24 hours<n>5.5 * 2 = <<5.5*2=11>>11 hours<n>24 + 11 = <<24+11=35>>35 hours<n>35/7 = <<35/7=5>>5 hours<n>Lawrence would work 5 hours each of the 7 days in a week.<n>So the final answer is 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. This is a case of no other choices.<n><n>Input:A group of students were studying for a test on multiplication. In that class, there were 21 students who had more than 2 hours of study time for each each day they had been practicing. There were 7 more students than the number of hours they studied in each day. How many hours per day did the students study?<n>Output:Let x = the number of hours they study a day.<n>21 + 7 = the total number of students.<n>The total number of hours is 21x + 7.<n>Adding 21x and 7 is x + 21x = <<21x+19=30>>30 hours.<n>Taking the positive square root of 30 for the x term, we get x =<<4=4>>4 hours.<n><n>Let's test that to make sure it makes sense: 21 * 4 = <<21*4=84>>84 hours, so x * 4 = <<x*4=32>>32 hours.<n>Adding 84 and 32 gives 116, so 84 + 32 = <<84+32=116>>116 hours.<n><n>7 * 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 hours.<n>116 + 28 = <<116+28=144>>144 hours.<n>The number of hours is 84 + 8 = <<84+8=92>>92 hours.<n>So the answer is 92 hours.<n><n>Input: A baker has 440 loaves of bread to deliver to market. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: Let x = the total number of candies Corey has.<n>x + 8 = the total number of candies Tapanga has.<n>The equation for the total number of candies is x + (x + 8) = 66<n>Combining like terms, we get 2x + 8 = 66<n>Subtracting 8 from both sides, we get 2x = 58<n>Dividing both sides by 2, we get x = <<29=29>>29, so Corey has 29 candies.<n>So the final answer is 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve.
